🧠 1. Hibernate Entity Lifecycle (SCN)
📌 Concept
An Entity (POJO mapped to DB table) moves through different states during its life.

🔄 Lifecycle States
State
Meaning
Transient
Object created using new, not in DB
Persistent
Managed by Hibernate, synced with DB
Detached
Was persistent, but no longer managed
Removed
Marked for deletion


⚙️ Approach (Flow)
Transient → Persistent → Detached → Removed


💻 Code Example
Product p = new Product();   // Transient

entityManager.persist(p);    // Persistent

entityManager.detach(p);     // Detached

entityManager.remove(p);     // Removed


🔑 Key Methods (EntityManager)
Method
Purpose
persist()
Save new entity
merge()
Reattach/update detached entity
remove()
Delete entity
find()
Fetch entity
detach()
Remove from persistence context
flush()
Sync with DB immediately


🎯 Learnings
Persistent state = auto DB sync
Detached objects are NOT tracked
merge() returns new managed object (important!)

🧠 2. Persistence Context (First-Level Cache)
📌 Concept
Persistence Context = cache where Hibernate stores managed entities
Also called First-Level Cache

⚙️ Behavior
One per transaction
Tracks changes automatically (Dirty Checking)
Avoids duplicate DB queries

💻 Example
Product p1 = entityManager.find(Product.class, 1);
Product p2 = entityManager.find(Product.class, 1);

// Only ONE query executed


🔑 Key Points
Same object instance returned
Changes auto-saved at commit
Improves performance

⚠️ Important Methods
Method
Use
clear()
Clears persistence context
contains()
Check if entity is managed
flush()
Force DB sync


🎯 Learnings
Core of Hibernate optimization
Works behind the scenes → very important for interviews

🧠 3. @Transactional (Spring)
📌 Concept
Ensures atomic execution of DB operations
Either all succeed OR all fail (rollback)

💻 Usage
@Transactional
public void createProduct() {
    repo.save(p1);
    repo.save(p2);
}


🔑 Important Attributes
@Transactional(
    readOnly = true,
    propagation = Propagation.REQUIRED,
    isolation = Isolation.READ_COMMITTED,
    rollbackFor = Exception.class
)


⚙️ Key Options
Attribute
Meaning
readOnly
Optimize read operations
propagation
Transaction behavior
isolation
Data consistency level
rollbackFor
Specify rollback condition


🔁 Propagation Types (Important)
Type
Meaning
REQUIRED
Default, join existing or create new
REQUIRES_NEW
Always new transaction
SUPPORTS
Runs if transaction exists
NOT_SUPPORTED
Runs without transaction


🎯 Learnings
Works with Persistence Context
Transaction commit → triggers DB sync
Without it → data may not persist properly

🧠 4. Important Hibernate / JPA Annotations
📌 Core Entity Annotations
Annotation
Purpose
@Entity
Marks class as DB entity
@Table
Specify table name
@Id
Primary key
@GeneratedValue
Auto-generate ID


📌 Column Mapping
Annotation
Purpose
@Column
Customize column
@Transient
Ignore field
@Enumerated
Enum mapping


📌 Lifecycle Callback Annotations
👉 Run automatically during entity lifecycle
Annotation
When Called
@PrePersist
Before insert
@PostPersist
After insert
@PreUpdate
Before update
@PostUpdate
After update
@PreRemove
Before delete
@PostRemove
After delete
@PostLoad
After fetch


💻 Example
@Entity
public class Product {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    @PrePersist
    public void beforeSave() {
        System.out.println("Saving...");
    }

    @PostLoad
    public void afterFetch() {
        System.out.println("Loaded...");
    }
}


🔑 Key Points
Callback methods must be:
void
No arguments
Used for:
Auditing
Logging
Auto timestamps

🔥 FINAL CONNECTION (Very Important)
🧩 How Everything Works Together
@Transactional starts transaction
Persistence Context is created
Entity becomes Persistent
Changes tracked (Dirty Checking)
On commit → Hibernate executes SQL
Lifecycle callbacks trigger automatically

🎯 Interview Summary (Quick Answer)
👉 Entity Lifecycle = states of entity (Transient → Persistent → Detached → Removed)
👉 Persistence Context = cache that manages entities
👉 @Transactional = ensures atomic DB operations
👉 Annotations = define mapping + lifecycle behavior



Good instinct—there are a few high-value points that usually get missed. Here are concise add-on notes to complete your understanding 👇

🔥 Important Missing Points (Quick Notes)
🧠 1. Dirty Checking (Core Hibernate Feature)
📌 Concept
Hibernate automatically detects changes in Persistent entities
No need to call update()
⚙️ How it works
Hibernate keeps a snapshot
On transaction commit → compares → generates SQL
💻 Example
Product p = entityManager.find(Product.class, 1);
p.setPrice(500);  // No save()

// On commit → UPDATE query runs automatically

🎯 Key Point
👉 Works only in Persistent state

🧠 2. Flush vs Commit (Very Important)
Feature
Flush
Commit
Meaning
Sync to DB
Finalize transaction
DB Query
Yes
Yes
Rollback possible
Yes
No

📌 Note
flush() ≠ commit
Data can still rollback after flush

🧠 3. Detach vs Clear
Method
Effect
detach(entity)
Removes single entity
clear()
Clears entire persistence context

👉 After detach → no dirty checking

🧠 4. Merge Behavior (Tricky Interview Point ⚠️)
Product detached = new Product();
Product managed = entityManager.merge(detached);

📌 Important
merge() returns new managed object
Original object is still detached
👉 Many candidates get this wrong

🧠 5. ReadOnly Transactions Optimization
@Transactional(readOnly = true)

📌 Benefits
Skips dirty checking
Improves performance
👉 Use for GET APIs

🧠 6. Lazy vs Eager Loading (Lifecycle Impact)
Type
Behavior
LAZY
Load when needed
EAGER
Load immediately

⚠️ Problem
👉 Lazy loading outside transaction → LazyInitializationException

🧠 7. Open Session in View (OSIV)
📌 Concept
Keeps session open till view layer
⚠️ Issue
Can hide lazy loading problems
Not recommended for production-heavy apps

🧠 8. Cascade Types (Lifecycle Link)
📌 Concept
Operations on parent affect child
Type
Meaning
PERSIST
Save child automatically
MERGE
Merge child
REMOVE
Delete child
ALL
Everything


🧠 9. Orphan Removal
@OneToMany(orphanRemoval = true)

👉 If child removed from collection → deleted from DB

🧠 10. Transaction Boundary Rule ⚠️
👉 Persistence Context lives inside transaction
No transaction → no proper lifecycle management
Always wrap DB logic in @Transactional

🧠 11. Exception Handling Rule
📌 Important
Only unchecked exceptions trigger rollback by default
@Transactional(rollbackFor = Exception.class)

👉 Needed for checked exceptions

🧠 12. N+1 Query Problem
📌 Problem
One query for parent + multiple for children
💡 Fix
Use JOIN FETCH
Use projections

🧠 13. Entity Equals & HashCode ⚠️
📌 Rule
Use ID-based equality
👉 Wrong implementation → bugs in persistence context

🧠 14. ID Generation Strategy Impact
Strategy
Behavior
IDENTITY
Insert immediately
SEQUENCE
Can batch
AUTO
Hibernate decides

👉 Affects performance + lifecycle timing

🎯 Final Takeaway
If you remember these 5 → you're solid:
Dirty Checking
Persistence Context scope
merge() behavior
Flush vs Commit
Lazy loading + transaction

